by bicycle. If you haven't realized it by now, we are addicted to bicycles. Since buying our first bicycles here, we have become constantly on the lookout for another pair. We even try to pre-buy Fat bicycles because they take a long time to ship.

We pulled into the Niger border with Fat bikes in hand for the ride to the town of Diffa where we basically sold them to the first nice looking taxi driver we spotted. He had spoken English, but we were able to communicate with pictsures and some french. The premium crossing rate we payed still netted us a profit of $550 each.

Backing our story up, we bought the bikes from a retired Canadian, in Mauritania, who had been living or driving them across most of Africa. He picked them up all new in China for a measly $300 each. Soon after, he was robbed in Mali when he took a wrong turn. It was a sad day for Fat Biking and his wife decided to sell them off in Burkina Faso.

We will have to bring them home and send em to the farmers. The world is running out of property to plow, and lighting up with plastic matches. We can't granny and gramps through this shit-fat, "earth care" !

Discovering just how much Indians like motorcycles.

The mountain bikes became unreliable to ride once getting into Pakistan. Following Elias's lead, we used the next empty plastic box we could get our hands on as makeshift vehicle
